foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos; this foliation is used throughout this record. Folios 193-202, ten blank leaves between ff. 192 and 203, were left unnumbered.
Numbering in pencil in the lower right-hand corner of the rectos; this foliation is ignored in this record.

signatures.p: Modern quire numbers in pencil added to the lower right corners of the first rectos of quires record; please note that the collation in this record deviates from the quire numbers added to the manuscript.

note.p: Folio 2v contains a poem with biblical references added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand: Est puer vnus hic Joh vjto et math viijo / Sunt pueri puri parui paruo satiati / Ludunt conformant cito dant cito pacificantur.

Folio 2v contains a note on the four types of vanity extracted from Gregory the Great's Moralia in Job added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand, beginning: Quatuor sunt species superbie quas assignat Gregorius h.32 [...] Prima est cum homo a seipso estimat habere bonum quod habet; and ending: Quarta quando despectis singulariter vult videri.
f. 257r features pen trials added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand: Surge deum lauda [...] / Parce michi virgo [...] / Sufficit tibi vera.

binding.p: Late 18th-century or 19th-century brown half leather binding with marbled paper sides; the spine with 5 raised bands and Red Russia leather with the gold-stamped inscription: Tracts M.S..

Parchment pastedowns on the inside covers with printed and handwritten text underneath. On the recto of the parchment pastedown on the front cover is an untranscribed 15th- or 16th century text, which is visible in reverse on the verso. Below the parchment pastedowns on both the front and rear covers are printed leaves with a form of Registers of Freeholders from the 28th year of the Reign of King George III (see Danby Pickering, The Statutes at Large From the Magna Charta, to the End of the Eleventh Parliament of Great Britain, Anno 1761 [continued to 1807] (Cambridge: Bentham, 1787), pp. 406-407).

provenance.p: An unknown owner with the surname Upton: inscribed in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand a prayer-request for Christ to protect their family and the manuscript on f. 2v: Dulcis semper ihesus vpton tueatur et librum.

Sir Thomas Knyvett (1539-1618) Knyvett, Thomas Sir, 1539-1618: Knyvett's shelfmark is inscribed in the lower margin of f. 257v: Sed. 27 (and is repeated by a modern hand on f. 1r: Knyvett Collection Sed. 27). See McKitterick (1978), p. 160 (MS 27).
Thomas Knyvett (1596-1658) Knyvett, Thomas, 1596-1658: grandson of Sir Thomas Knyvett 1539-1618, inherited this manuscript together with Knyvett's collection. See McKitterick (1978), pp. 33-34..

John Knyvett (1623-1673) Knyvett, John, 1623-1673: great-grandson of Sir Thomas Knyvett 1539-1618 and son of Thomas Knyvett (1596-1658), inherited this manuscript together with Knyvett's collection. See McKitterick (1978), p. 36 .

Thomas Knyvett (d. 1693) Knyvett, Thomas, d. 1693: great-great-grandson of Sir Thomas Knyvett 1539-1618 and son of John Knyvett (1623-1673), inherited this manuscript together with Knyvett's collection. Thomas died without heir and the Knyvett library was fragmented after his death: 57 of Knyvett's manuscripts had been acquired by John Moore [see below] by 1698. See McKitterick (1978), p. 37.
John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 : no. 177 in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (c. 1697).

history.acquisition: Presented to the University Library in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 : but without the usual donation bookplate engraved by John Pine Pine, John, 1690-1756 in 1736.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on Margaret Connolly, Manuscripts in the University Library, Cambridge (Dd-Oo), The Index of Middle English Prose (Woodbridge: Brewer, 2009) and an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1926 and 1930 by M.R. James James, M.R. (Montague Rhodes), 1862-1936, now held in the University Archives (UA ULIB 7/3/74).

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.

msItem.title: Recipe for making a medical water
msItem.incipit: 256v Sage lauander Avans bay leves faciunt aqua redolente
msItem.note: Full transcription; added by the same late 15th- or early 16th-century hand that added the Middle English recipes for the pox and sciatica on f. 256r. This recipe is not recorded in Connolly (2009).

supportDesc.support: Paper, folded in folio. Folios 226-256: Dragon ( 25 70 ) in the centre of the folio.

collation.signatures: Leaf signatures consisting of letters ('a'-'d') and Roman numerals; note the irregularity in Quire 18, where 'iiijd' precedes 'iijd' because the third and fourth bifolia have been misbound.

catchwords.seg: Catchwords written in brown ink on the last versos of quires.

supportDesc.condition: The upper halves of the leaves have been affected by water.

p.seg: Ruled in leadpoint, frame and line ruling. Double columns. 41 lines to the page, written below top line.

handNote.p: ff. 226r-255v have been copied by a single scribe in a cursive script with both Secretary and Anglicana features.

decoNote.p: Large (2-3 lines) initials in red ink.
